<h2> Consoles Reference</h2>

<ul class = 'center-text'></ul>

  <div class = 'definitions margin-auto no-list-style'>
    
    <li>
      <b>Atari</b>: One of the earlier video game consoles. It was released in 1982.
    </li><br>
    
    <li>
      <b>NES</b>: This represents Nintendo's first video game console. It was released in 1983 and features an 8 bit processor.
    </li><br>
    
    <li>
      <b>Super Nintendo(SNES)</b>: As Nintendo's second console, this was released in 1990. This console has a more powerful 16 bit       processor.
    </li><br>
    
    <li>
      <b>Nintendo 64</b>: Released in 1996, this was Nintendo's third console as well as the successor to the SNES. It includes a 64       bit CPU and was the last Nintendo console to store games in ROM cartridges. It competed with Sony's first console, Playstation.
    </li><br>
    
    <li>
      <b>GameCube</b>: Released in 2001, this was the successor to the Nintendo 64. Unlike the previous three Nintendo consoles, this       one used optical discs as its primary storage medium. As a sixth generation console, it's primary competition was the Playstation2 and Xbox.
    </li><br>
    
    <li>
      <b>Nintendo Wii</b>: Released in 2006, this was the GameCube successor. It made headlines for its innovative remote. As a seventh       generation console, it's primary competition was the Playstation 3 and Xbox360.
    </li><br>
    
    <li>
      <b>Nintendo Wii U</b>: Released in 2011, this was Wii's successor. This is an eighth generation console.
    </li><br>
    
    <li>
      <b>Nintendo DS</b>: Released in 2004, this is a handheld console released by Nintendo
    </li><br>
    
    <li>
      <b>Genesis</b>: Released in 1988, this was Sega's first video game console. As a fourth generation console, it competed with the       Super Nintendo in the 16-bit market.
    </li><br>
    
    <li>
      <b>Dreamcast</b>: Released in 1999 and discontinued in 2001, this was unfortunately Sega's most disappointing console. It       couldn't compete with Nintendo and Sony.
    </li><br>
    
    <li>
      <b>Playstation</b>: Released in 1995, this was Sony's first console. As a fifth generation console, it competed directly with the       Nintendo 64 and Sega Dreamcast.
    </li><br>
    
    <li>
      <b>Playstation 2</b>: The successor to the Playstation, this was released in 2000. As a sixth generation console, it's                  competition was Nintendo's GameCube and Microsoft's first console, Xbox 360.
    </li><br>
    
    <li>
      <b>Playstation 3</b>: The successor to the Playstation 3, this was released in 2006
    </li><br>
    
    <li>
      <b>PC</b>: This console is a Personal Computer.
    </li><br>
    
    <li>
      <b>Xbox</b>: Released in 2001, this console represents Microsoft's first foray into the Gaming Console Industry. As a sixth       generation console, it competed for market share with Nintendo's GameCube and Sony's Playstation.
    </li><br>
    
    <li>
      <b>Xbox360</b>: Released in 2006, this is the successor to the Xbox. As a seventh generation console, it competed for market      share with Nintendo's Wii and Sony's Playstation 2.
    </li><br>
    
  </div>
  
</ul>

